'2:4': [
{sup:1, word:"removed", lines:["Their zeal in seeking the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s healing compelled the seekers to break through the proper barrier&mdash;a wild act. See {Mat9:2^1|note 2<sup>1</sup>} in {Mat9|Matt. 9}."]},
{sup:"a", word:"roof", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Sam. 9:25; Neh. 8:16; Acts 10:9"},
{sup:2, word:"mat", lines:["A small mattress or pad. So in vv. {Mrk2:9|9}, {Mrk2:11|11}, and {Mrk2:12|12}."]},
],
'2:5': [
{sup:"1a", word:"faith", vrefs:"Mark 10:52; Matt. 8:10, 13; 9:22, 29; 15:28; Luke 7:50; 17:19; 18:42; Acts 14:9", lines:["Faith here, which issues from hearing the word of Christ ({Rom10:17|Rom. 10:17}), indicates that the seekers had heard of the Slave-Savior."]},
{sup:2, word:"Child", lines:["This loving word spoken by the Slave-Savior implies kindness; in this His human virtue was expressed."]},
{sup:3, word:"sins", lines:["Sins are the cause of sickness. The Slave-Savior&rsquo;s word here touched the cause of sickness so that a healing effect could come. Once the sins had been forgiven, the sickness was healed."]},
{sup:"b", word:"forgiven", vrefs:"Luke 7:48; James 5:15"},
],
'2:6': [
{sup:1, word:"scribes", lines:["The scribes and Pharisees, as the religionists of the old and dead religion, were motivated and used by Satan, the enemy of God, to oppose, resist, and frustrate the gospel service of the Slave of God throughout His ministry (vv. {Mrk2:16|16}, {Mrk2:24|24}; {Mrk3:22|3:22}; {Mrk7:5|7:5}; {Mrk8:11|8:11}; {Mrk9:14|9:14}; {Mrk10:2|10:2}; {Mrk11:27|11:27}; {Mrk12:13|12:13}, {Mrk12:28|28}). They thought that they were worshipping God and were zealous for Him, not knowing that the very God of their forefathers&mdash;Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob&mdash;was immediately in front of them in the form of a Slave who desired to serve them. Blinded by their traditional religion from seeing Him in the divine economy, they plotted to kill Him ({Mrk3:6|3:6}; {Mrk11:18|11:18}; {Mrk14:1|14:1}); and they actually did kill Him ({Mrk8:31|8:31}; {Mrk10:33|10:33}; {Mrk14:43|14:43}, {Mrk14:53|53}; {Mrk15:1|15:1}, {Mrk15:31|31})."]},
],
'2:7': [
{sup:"a", word:"blaspheming", vrefs:"Mark 14:64; John 10:36"},
{sup:"b", word:"sins", vrefs:"Psa. 32:5; Isa. 43:25"},
{sup:1, word:"God", lines:["The reasoning scribes, who considered themselves to be according to the Scriptures and theology, acknowledged the Slave-Savior merely as a man, even a despised Nazarene ({Joh1:45|John 1:45}-{Joh1:46|46}), not realizing that the One who forgave the sins of the paralytic was the very forgiving God incarnated in the form of a lowly man (see {Mat9:3^2|note 3<sup>2</sup>} in {Mat9|Matt. 9}), who came as a Slave to serve them with His salvation."]},
],
'2:8': [
{sup:"a", word:"immediately", vrefs:"Mark 1:42, 43; 2:12"},
{sup:"1b", word:"knowing", vrefs:"John 2:25", lines:["The Slave-Savior knew the seekers&rsquo; faith, the sick one&rsquo;s sins ({Mrk2:5|v. 5}), and the scribes&rsquo; inward reasoning; this indicates that He was omniscient. Such omniscience, which manifested His divine attribute, unveiled His deity, showing that He is the omniscient God. See {Mrk11:2^1|note 2<sup>1</sup>} in {Mrk11|ch. 11}."]},
],
'2:9': [
{sup:1, word:"easier", lines:["See {Mat9:5^1|note 5<sup>1</sup>} in {Mat9|Matt. 9}."]},
],
'2:10': [
{sup:"a", word:"Son", vrefs:"Mark 2:28"},
{sup:1, word:"Man", lines:["The Slave-Savior was the very God incarnated. As such, He did not consider being equal with God a treasure to be grasped. Outwardly, He was in the likeness and fashion of man, even in the form of a slave, but inwardly, He was God ({Phi2:6|Phil. 2:6}-{Phi2:7|7}). He was the Slave-Savior, and the God-Savior as well. Hence, He had not only the ability to save sinners but also the authority to forgive their sins. In this incident, although He as God forgave people&rsquo;s sins, He asserted that He was the Son of Man. This indicates that He was the true God and a real man, possessing deity and humanity. In Him men could see both His divine attributes and His human virtues."]},
],
'2:11': [
{sup:1, word:"Rise", lines:["See {Mat9:5^2|note 5<sup>2</sup>} in {Mat9|Matt. 9}. This was the healing of the paralytic. See {Mrk1:31^1|note 31<sup>1</sup>} in {Mrk1|ch. 1}."]},
{sup:"a", word:"take", vrefs:"John 5:8"},
],
'2:12': [
{sup:1, word:"rose", lines:["This is the fulfillment of the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s word, &ldquo;Rise, take up your mat.&rdquo; It was easier to say, &ldquo;Your sins are forgiven,&rdquo; than to say, &ldquo;Rise and take up your mat and walk.&rdquo; Since the latter word was fulfilled, surely the former also, the easier one, had been fulfilled. This is strong evidence that the Slave-Savior has authority to forgive sins on earth."]},
{sup:2, word:"took", lines:["See {Mat9:6^2|note 6<sup>2</sup>} in {Mat9|Matt. 9}."]},
{sup:3, word:"went", lines:["See {Mat9:6^3|note 6<sup>3</sup>} in {Mat9|Matt. 9}."]},
{sup:"a", word:"amazed", vrefs:"Mark 1:27; 5:42"},
{sup:"b", word:"glorified", vrefs:"Luke 7:16"},
],
'2:13': [
{sup:"a", word:"sea", vrefs:"Mark 1:16; 3:7"},
{sup:"b", word:"crowd", vrefs:"Mark 1:45; 3:7-9; 5:24"},
{sup:1, word:"taught", lines:["See {Mrk1:21^2|note 21<sup>2</sup>} in {Mrk1|ch. 1}."]},
],
'2:14': [
{sup:1, word:"And", lines:["For vv. {Mrk2:14|14}-{Mrk2:17|17}, see {Mat9:9^1|notes} in {Mat9:9|Matt. 9:9}-{Mat9:13|13}."]},
{sup:"2a", word:"tax", vrefs:"vv. 14-17: Matt. 9:9-13; Luke 5:27-32", lines:["A tollhouse, where taxes for the Romans were collected. Matthew was one of the tax collectors ({Mat10:3|Matt. 10:3}), probably in a high position. Tax collectors were condemned, despised, and abhorred by the Jews ({Luk18:11|Luke 18:11}; {Mat5:46|Matt. 5:46} and {Mat5:46^2|note 2}). Yet Matthew was called by the Slave-Savior and was later chosen and appointed as one of the twelve apostles ({Mrk3:18|3:18}). What mercy!"]},
{sup:3, word:"followed", lines:["As an answer to the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s call, this action implied that he was abandoning his dirty job and his sinful life."]},
],
'2:15': [
{sup:"a", word:"tax", vrefs:"Matt. 11:19; Luke 15:1-2; 18:10-14"},
],
'2:16': [
{sup:"1a", word:"scribes", vrefs:"Acts 4:5; 23:9", lines:["See {Mrk2:6^1|note 6<sup>1</sup>}. The scribes were self-righteous in condemning the Slave-Savior for His feasting with tax collectors and sinners."]},
],
