'14:20': [
{sup:1, word:"one", lines:["After being exposed, Judas left ({Joh13:21|John 13:21}-{Joh13:30|30}) before the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s supper ({Mat26:20|Matt. 26:20}-{Mat26:26|26}). He did not participate in the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s body and blood, because he was not a real believer in Him but a son of perdition ({Joh17:12|John 17:12}), considered by the Slave-Savior even a devil ({Joh6:70|John 6:70}-{Joh6:71|71}). {Luk22:21|Luke 22:21}-{Luk22:23|23} seems to indicate that Judas left after the Lord&rsquo;s supper, which is mentioned in {Luk22:19|Luke 22:19}-{Luk22:20|20}. However, Mark&rsquo;s record, like Matthew&rsquo;s, shows that Judas was identified by the Slave-Savior as His betrayer (vv. {Mrk14:18|18}-{Mrk14:21|21}) before He instituted His supper (vv. {Mrk14:22|22}-{Mrk14:24|24}). Mark&rsquo;s record is according to historical sequence, whereas Luke&rsquo;s sequence is according to morality. See {Mat8:16^1P2|note 16<sup>1</sup>, par. 2}, in {Mat8|Matt. 8}."]},
],
'14:21': [
{sup:1, word:"going", lines:["This refers to His going to die."]},
{sup:"a", word:"written", vrefs:"Mark 9:12; Luke 24:46"},
],
'14:22': [
{sup:1, word:"And", lines:["For vv. {Mrk14:22|22}-{Mrk14:26|26}, see {Mat26:26^1|notes} in {Mat26:26|Matt. 26:26}-{Mat26:30|30}."]},
{sup:2, word:"eating", lines:["This was the eating of the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s supper, after He and His followers had eaten the passover feast in vv. {Mrk14:16|16}-{Mrk14:18|18}. He initiated this new feast, which was for His believers&rsquo; remembrance of Him, to replace the passover feast, the old testament feast for the elect&rsquo;s remembrance of Jehovah&rsquo;s salvation ({Exo12:14|Exo. 12:14}; {Exo13:3|13:3}). This new feast of the new testament is for the remembering of the Slave-Savior through the eating of the bread, which signifies His body given for His believers ({1Co11:24|1&nbsp;Cor. 11:24}), and the drinking of the cup, which signifies His blood shed for their sins ({Mat26:28|Matt. 26:28}). The bread denotes life ({Joh6:35|John 6:35}), the life of God, the eternal life, and the cup denotes blessing ({1Co10:16|1&nbsp;Cor. 10:16}), which is God Himself as the believers&rsquo; portion ({Psa16:5|Psa. 16:5}). As sinners, the believers should have had the cup of God&rsquo;s wrath as their portion ({Rev14:10|Rev. 14:10}). But the Slave-Savior drank that cup for them ({Joh18:11|John 18:11}), and His salvation became their portion, the cup of salvation ({Psa116:13|Psa. 116:13}) that runs over ({Psa23:5|Psa. 23:5}), the content of which is God as the believers&rsquo; all-inclusive blessing. Such a bread and such a cup are the constituents of the Slave-Savior&rsquo;s supper, which is a table ({1Co10:21|1&nbsp;Cor. 10:21}), a feast, set up by Him that His believers may remember Him by enjoying Him as such a feast. Thus, as His believers remember Him, they display His redeeming and life-imparting death ({1Co11:26|1&nbsp;Cor. 11:26}&mdash;His blood separated from His body declares His death), testifying to the entire universe of His rich and marvelous salvation."]},
{sup:"a", word:"bread", vrefs:"vv. 22-25: Matt. 26:26-29; Luke 22:19-20; 1&nbsp;Cor. 11:23-26"},
{sup:"b", word:"blessed", vrefs:"Mark 8:7; Matt. 14:19"},
{sup:"c", word:"body", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Cor. 10:16"},
],
'14:24': [
{sup:"a", word:"blood", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Cor. 10:16; Heb. 13:20; cf. Exo. 24:8; Zech. 9:11"},
{sup:1, word:"covenant", lines:["In {Exo24:3|Exo. 24:3}-{Exo24:8|8} God made a covenant with redeemed Israel ({Heb9:18|Heb. 9:18}-{Heb9:21|21}), which became the old testament, as a base from which He could deal with His redeemed people in the dispensation of law. The Slave-Savior came to accomplish God&rsquo;s eternal redemption for God&rsquo;s chosen people by His death, according to God&rsquo;s will ({Heb10:7|Heb. 10:7}, {Heb10:9|9}-{Heb10:10|10}), and with His blood He instituted a new covenant, a better covenant ({Heb8:6|Heb. 8:6}-{Heb8:13|13}), which after His resurrection became the new testament ({Heb9:16|Heb. 9:16}-{Heb9:17|17}), as a base from which God can be one with His redeemed and regenerated people in the dispensation of grace. This new covenant replaced the old covenant and at the same time changed God&rsquo;s old dispensation to His new dispensation. The Slave-Savior wanted His followers to know this and to live a life based on this and according to this after His resurrection."]},
{sup:"b", word:"many", vrefs:"Mark 10:45"},
],
